   =20
      ChatGPT
   =20
 =20

The  stereotype of  ChatGPT, Open AI=E2=80=99s publicly available conversat=
ional large language model, is that if you ask it a technical question it w=
ill give you an answer that is confident and plausible but not necessarily =
correct. This is of course an incredibly=C2=A0useful skill, and a very good=
 model of a certain sort of human intelligence; ChatGPT seems dangerous as =
a software engineer but could have a good run as an investment banker.
  [1]

How is it as an asset manager, or at least an asset-management salesrobot? =
Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Sam Potter and Katherine Greifeld   gave it a go:

In a bid to see how close technology really is to replacing Wall Street=E2=
=80=99s army of analysts, experts and money runners, we challenged ChatGPT,=
 the artificial intelligence tool that=E2=80=99s taking the internet by sto=
rm, to create us a winning portfolio for the US stock market.=C2=A0
The result: A classic exercise in fence-sitting, with the tool explaining t=
hat the market is too unpredictable to design such a fund, while warning ab=
out the need to pick investments aligning with our goals and appetite for r=
isk-taking.

=E2=80=9CIt is not possible for me to design an ETF that will beat the US s=
tock market because the stock market is unpredictable and past performance =
does not guarantee future results,=E2=80=9D ChatGPT says, disappointingly, =
adding a bunch of not-investing-advice boilerplate. Bleh. I would have expe=
cted more unearned confidence. Like I=E2=80=99d expect it to come up with a=
 list of 50 tickers, no problem; I just wouldn=E2=80=99t expect them to bea=
t the market, and maybe a couple of them would not correspond to actual sto=
cks.
You can do better, where by =E2=80=9Cbetter=E2=80=9D I mean =E2=80=9Cget mo=
re confident answers out of ChatGPT=E2=80=9D rather than =E2=80=9Cactually =
get it to beat the market for you.=E2=80=9D Last month  Robin Wigglesworth =
at the Financial Times wrote about a quantitative research analyst who got =
ChatGPT to write research notes for him; they were, you know, adequate.=C2=
=A0And I   once wrote about GPT-2, an earlier large language model:

If you trained it on a bunch of Warren Buffett annual letters maybe it woul=
d say some stuff that sounds like Warren Buffett? Not just in terms of=C2=
=A0folksy sex jokes=C2=A0but also in terms of penetrating investment insigh=
t? Maybe GPT-2 would digest Buffett=E2=80=99s mind, or rather specifically =
the parts of Buffett=E2=80=99s mind that are exposed when he writes prose, =
and it would use that understanding of his mind to write Buffett-like prose=
 recommending Buffett-like investing decisions?
Or if you run an investment firm and you=E2=80=99ve got a corpus of memos f=
rom your analysts recommending investment decisions, why not take the memos=
 that=C2=A0worked out=E2=80=94the ones recommending investments that went u=
p=E2=80=94and feed them into GPT-2? Then have it write you a new memo and s=
ee if it=E2=80=99s any good?

I wouldn=E2=80=99t bet on it or anything; it=E2=80=99s interesting to specu=
late about, but it seems unlikely that a computer will get good at=C2=A0mak=
ing investment decisions just by ingesting how humans have=C2=A0articulated=
=C2=A0investment=C2=A0decisions. (It=E2=80=99s much more likely to fixate o=
n boilerplate about how =E2=80=9Cpast performance does not guarantee future=
 results.=E2=80=9D) But I bet a computer could get pretty good at=C2=A0arti=
culating=C2=A0investment decisions from that training set. (In a sense this=
 is the opposite of a classic =E2=80=9Cblack box=E2=80=9D machine-learning =
investment algorithm: Classic quant signals might work, but=20
you can=E2=80=99t explain them; ChatGPT might not work, but it can explain =
itself.)=C2=A0If your hedge fund lost money last year, maybe ask ChatGPT to=
 write your investor letter for you. It can spin up some platitudes, quote =
some Stoic philosophers, and sound confident and plausible, which is all yo=
u really need for the=C2=A0letter.=C2=A0

