We   talked yesterday about a glitch at the New York Stock Exchange on Tues=
day: NYSE forgot to do the opening auction for a bunch of stocks, instead g=
oing straight into ordinary trading at 9:30 a.m. It turns out this is bad: =
If you take the orders for the opening auction and just put them into the r=
egular trading order book, prices bounce around wildly and you end up havin=
g to cancel a bunch of trades. The stock market works one way in the openin=
g auction at 9:30:00, and a different way in regular trading at 9:30:01, an=
d if you mix them up you get a mess.
But how did NYSE mix them up? Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Katherine Doherty repor=
ts:

More than 700 miles from Wall Street, the New York Stock Exchange=E2=80=99s=
 backup data center on Cermak Road in Chicago is supposed to safeguard US m=
arkets, standing by at all hours in case disaster ever strikes the world=E2=
=80=99s largest venue for trading shares.
When markets are closed, it participates in a well-worn routine, with NYSE =
staffers turning on and off systems to ensure everything works. But heading=
 into Tuesday, an NYSE employee failed to properly shut down Cermak=E2=80=
=99s disaster-recovery system =E2=80=94 leading to a disaster. ...
The turmoil resulted because the backup system in Cermak was left running. =
That misled the exchange=E2=80=99s computers to treat the 9:30 a.m. opening=
 bell as a continuation of trading, and so they skipped the day=E2=80=99s o=
pening auctions that neatly set initial prices.

Eep. I wrote yesterday that =E2=80=9Cthe stock market goes to bed at 4 p.m.=
 and wakes up at 9:30 a.m. the next day.=E2=80=9D But in fact, when NYSE=C2=
=A0goes to bed at 4 p.m.,=C2=A0it spends the night dreaming that it is stil=
l processing trades. And then it wakes up at 9:30 a.m. the next day to proc=
ess more trades. On Tuesday, it kept dreaming through its 9:30 alarm clock,=
 and chaos resulted.=C2=A0
Incidentally! The US Securities and Exchange Commission has=C2=A0 proposed =
new rules that would significantly change how retail stock trading works. O=
versimplifying enormously, the way it works now is that retail brokers send=
 their customers=E2=80=99 orders to electronic market making firms, who tra=
de directly with those orders, buying from the customers who want to sell a=
nd selling to the ones who want to buy and paying the brokers a bit for the=
 privilege. And the SEC=E2=80=99s proposal would require the brokers to ins=
tead send those orders to a=C2=A0stock exchange, like NYSE or Nasdaq, which=
 would then=C2=A0run an auction=C2=A0to decide who trades with the retail o=
rder.
  [3]
=C2=A0We discussed the proposals in more detail last month; my headline was=
 =E2=80=9CThe SEC Wants More Stock Auctions.=E2=80=9D
The fact that NYSE messed up a bunch of stock auctions this week, and mild =
chaos resulted, seems mildly bad for that plan? One thing about US market s=
tructure is that there are  a dozen or so stock exchanges, and you can trad=
e all the stocks on all of them, and if one of them shuts down at 11 a.m. d=
ue to a blown fuse or whatever, you just trade at another exchange and ever=
ything works fine. But there are only two main listing exchanges =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0NYSE and Nasdaq =E2=80=94=C2=A0and stocks are normally listed at one =
or the other, and the opening and closing auction for each stock happens on=
ly on its listing exchange. Yesterday, when NYSE forgot to do its opening a=
uction, that caused chaos everywhere; trading on other exchanges could not =
compensate for the problem with NYSE=E2=80=99s auctions.=C2=A0
I guess you might worry that if NYSE did hundreds of auctions per day in ea=
ch stock, instead of two, there would be more problems. If you were a retai=
l broker or electronic market maker, and you like the current system and wo=
uld be inconvenienced by the SEC=E2=80=99s proposals, you might argue that,=
 anyway. Doherty reports:

Charles Schwab Corp., the brokerage catering to retail investors, openly cr=
iticized the NYSE on Wednesday, saying it=E2=80=99s disappointed by how the=
 incident was handled and that individuals may not get a fair shake when it=
 comes to compensation. Schwab said the episode should also raise concerns =
about regulatory proposals that could push more trading onto stock exchange=
s.
=E2=80=9CUnfortunately, the NYSE has not owned up to their full responsibil=
ity and retail investors will have to go through a lengthy process to corre=
ct orders, with no guarantee of a reasonable outcome,=E2=80=9D Schwab spoke=
sperson Mayura Hooper said. =E2=80=9CIt further heightens our concerns that=
 routing even greater levels of retail orders to the exchanges will dramati=
cally reduce the quality of the investing experience for America=E2=80=99s =
retail investors.=E2=80=9D

NYSE picked sort of an awkward time to mess up its auctions, is the point h=
ere.

