me on, obviously Elon is gonna pay, Twitter has the money and it=E2=80=99d =
be crazy not to=E2=80=9D:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By all accounts =E2=80=94 including Elon Musk=
=E2=80=99s =E2=80=94 Twitter has more than enough money to make its first i=
nterest payments, expected to total about $300 million. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A group of seven banks, led by Morgan Stanley,=
 own the debt. =E2=80=A6 Now, after they lost some $4 billion on paper for =
backing Musk=E2=80=99s Twitter bid, market onlookers see little reason for =
the banks to go along with any unexpected maneuvers near the interest-payme=
nt deadline, roughly around Jan. 27.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After all, in most bankruptcies, the equity is=
 wiped out =E2=80=94 and lenders eventually take control.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s too much at stake for=
 Musk and his co-investors,=E2=80=9D said Jordan Chalfin, a senior analyst =
at credit research firm CreditSights. =E2=80=9CTwitter will make its near-t=
erm interest payments, come hell or high water, and give the business time =
to turn around.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand =E2=80=A6=C2=A0it=E2=80=99s =
