<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/30369314.268448/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMjUvbnlzZS1mb3Jnb3QtdG8tb3Blbi15ZXN0ZXJkYXk_Y21waWQ9=
QkJEMDEyNjIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR=
0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwMTI2JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB7d7f8b12" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">  talked yesterday</a> about a glitch at the New =
York Stock Exchange on Tuesday: NYSE forgot to do the opening auction for a=
 bunch of stocks, instead going straight into ordinary trading at 9:30 a.m.=
 It turns out this is bad: If you take the orders for the opening auction a=
nd just put them into the regular trading order book, prices bounce around =
wildly and you end up having to cancel a bunch of trades. The stock market =
works one way in the opening auction at 9:30:00, and a different way in reg=
ular trading at 9:30:01, and if you mix them up you get a mess.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But how did NYSE mix them up? Bloomberg=E2=80=
=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30369314.2684=
48/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDEtMjUvbnlz=
ZS1tYXloZW0tdHJhY2VkLXRvLWEtc3RhZmZlci13aG8tbGVmdC1hLWJhY2t1cC1zeXN0ZW0tcnV=
ubmluZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMTI2MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3=
VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzAxMjYmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB242f81a5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Katherine Doherty reports</a>:<=
/p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">More than 700 miles from Wall Street, the New =
York Stock Exchange=E2=80=99s backup data center on Cermak Road in Chicago =
is supposed to safeguard US markets, standing by at all hours in case disas=
ter ever strikes the world=E2=80=99s largest venue for trading shares.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When markets are closed, it participates in a =
well-worn routine, with NYSE staffers turning on and off systems to ensure =
everything works. But heading into Tuesday, an NYSE employee failed to prop=
erly shut down Cermak=E2=80=99s disaster-recovery system =E2=80=94 leading =
to a disaster. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The turmoil resulted because the backup system=
 in Cermak was left running. That misled the exchange=E2=80=99s computers t=
o treat the 9:30 a.m. opening bell as a continuation of trading, and so the=
y skipped the day=E2=80=99s opening auctions that neatly set initial prices=
.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Eep. I wrote yesterday that =E2=80=9Cthe stock=
 market goes to bed at 4 p.m. and wakes up at 9:30 a.m. the next day.=E2=80=
=9D But in fact, when NYSE=C2=A0goes to bed at 4 p.m.,=C2=A0it spends the n=
ight dreaming that it is still processing trades. And then it wakes up at 9=
:30 a.m. the next day to process more trades. On Tuesday, it kept dreaming =
through its 9:30 alarm clock, and chaos resulted.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Incidentally! The US Securities and Exchange C=
ommission has=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click=
/30369314.268448/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGVhc2UvMjAyMi=
0yMjU/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe0db6eec" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> proposed new rules</a> =
that would significantly change how retail stock trading works. Oversimplif=
ying enormously, the way it works now is that retail brokers send their cus=
tomers=E2=80=99 orders to electronic market making firms, who trade directl=
y with those orders, buying from the customers who want to sell and selling=
 to the ones who want to buy and paying the brokers a bit for the privilege=
. And the SEC=E2=80=99s proposal would require the brokers to instead send =
those orders to a=C2=A0<em>stock exchange</em>, like NYSE or Nasdaq, which =
would then=C2=A0<em>run an auction=C2=A0</em>to decide who trades with the =
retail order.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background=
-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0We discussed the proposals in more detail last month; my headline=
 was =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/3036=
9314.268448/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjI=
tMTItMTUvdGhlLXNlYy13YW50cy1tb3JlLXN0b2NrLWF1Y3Rpb25zP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMjYyM1=
9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90Z=
XJtPTIzMDEyNiZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6e3e=
a5c5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;">The SEC Wants More Stock Auctions</a>.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The fact that NYSE messed up a bunch of stock =
auctions this week, and mild chaos resulted, seems mildly bad for that plan=
? One thing about US market structure is that there are <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30369314.268448/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjL=
mdvdi9kaXZpc2lvbnMvbWFya2V0cmVnL21yZXhjaGFuZ2VzLnNodG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB8d752463" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> a dozen or so</a> stock exchanges, and you can tra=
de all the stocks on all of them, and if one of them shuts down at 11 a.m. =
due to a blown fuse or whatever, you just trade at another exchange and eve=
rything works fine. But there are only two main listing exchanges =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0NYSE and Nasdaq =E2=80=94=C2=A0and stocks are normally listed at one =
or the other, and the opening and closing auction for each stock happens on=
ly on its listing exchange. Yesterday, when NYSE forgot to do its opening a=
uction, that caused chaos everywhere; trading on other exchanges could not =
compensate for the problem with NYSE=E2=80=99s auctions.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess you might worry that if NYSE did hundr=
eds of auctions per day in each stock, instead of two, there would be more =
problems. If you were a retail broker or electronic market maker, and you l=
ike the current system and would be inconvenienced by the SEC=E2=80=99s pro=
posals, you might argue that, anyway. Doherty reports:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Charles Schwab Corp., the brokerage catering t=
o retail investors, openly criticized the NYSE on Wednesday, saying it=E2=
=80=99s disappointed by how the incident was handled and that individuals m=
ay not get a fair shake when it comes to compensation. Schwab said the epis=
ode should also raise concerns about regulatory proposals that could push m=
ore trading onto stock exchanges.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CUnfortunately, the NYSE has not owned=
 up to their full responsibility and retail investors will have to go throu=
gh a lengthy process to correct orders, with no guarantee of a reasonable o=
utcome,=E2=80=9D Schwab spokesperson Mayura Hooper said. =E2=80=9CIt furthe=
r heightens our concerns that routing even greater levels of retail orders =
to the exchanges will dramatically reduce the quality of the investing expe=
rience for America=E2=80=99s retail investors.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">NYSE picked sort of an awkward time to mess up=
 its auctions, is the point here.</p>
