cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  before</a>, the basic premise o=
f a lot of crypto is that every product is simultaneously an investment opp=
ortunity. The day that this project =E2=80=94=C2=A0Pollen, Helium, whatever=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0launches, (1) nobody is providing service on its network an=
d (2) nobody is using its network. The project is only good if it achieves =
scale and network effects: You=E2=80=99ll only provide service if people us=
e the network, and you=E2=80=99ll only use the network if people provide se=
rvice. It=E2=80=99s hard to incentivize people to=C2=A0<em>start</em>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Crypto =E2=80=94=C2=A0or, more specifically, t=
he crypto=C2=A0<em>boom=C2=A0</em>that=C2=A0sort of ended last spring =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0was a way to solve this problem. Instead of =E2=80=9Cbuy our de=
vice and start providing wireless coverage, and if a lot of people do that =
then people will use the coverage, and then maybe one day they=E2=80=99ll p=
ay you,=E2=80=9D it was =E2=80=9Cbuy our device and start providing wireles=
s coverage, and we=E2=80=99ll=C2=A0<em>give you lots of tokens</em>, and if=
 this thing takes off then the tokens will be valuable and you=E2=80=99ll b=
e able to buy an island, for providing this wireless coverage in the early =
days of our network.=E2=80=9D It was a way to turn this possibly useful ser=
vice into=C2=A0<em>also a Ponzi scheme:=C2=A0</em>You get rich if more peop=
le come into the project after you. But if more people come into the projec=
t after you, then it will actually provide a useful service (wireless cover=
age), and maybe the economics will work out. It=E2=80=99s a little bit of P=
onzi to bootstrap a real business with network effects.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One problem is that if this works and you get =
a lot of people to get your device and plug it in and provide the wireless =
coverage, the next step is to get people to use it=C2=A0and pay for it. And=
 so you have to go to a whole new set of people and be like =E2=80=9Chi, wo=
uld you like to fly a drone in rural areas? Good news, you can use our wire=
less service!=E2=80=9D And they are like =E2=80=9Chmm I=E2=80=99m intereste=
d,=E2=80=9D and you continue: =E2=80=9CGreat! You=E2=80=99ll need our token=
s to pay for the service. What you do is you set up a MetaMask wallet and b=
uy some Ether, and then you go to a decentralized exchange to swap it for=
=E2=80=9D but they have already wandered away.=C2=A0Come on! You can find s=
ome hobbyists at the overlap between =E2=80=9Cwant to set up a public WiFi =
device in their home=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Care into crypto,=E2=80=9D or at =
least you could in February 2022, but you will have a harder time finding a=
 lot of people who want to get deep into crypto just to get internet access=
.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So a natural thing to do is, as=C2=A0your netw=
ork grows, you say =E2=80=9Cokay fine you can just pay for our service usin=
g a credit card like a normal person.=E2=80=9D But then =E2=80=A6=C2=A0what=
 are the tokens for? Nothing, the answer is nothing. You used a Ponzi schem=
e to build a real service, and then you ran the real service like a regular=
 business. What happens to the token holders?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway Pollen <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/30369314.268448/aHR0cHM6Ly9tZWRpdW0uY29tL0Bwb2xsZW=
5tb2JpbGUvdGhlLW5leHQtcGhhc2UtZm9yLXBvbGxlbi1tb2JpbGUtcGFpZC1kYXRhLTUzYjRlM=
TFjN2Zh/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBae5560d0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> put up a Medium post</a=
> this week saying that =E2=80=9CIn conjunction with officially announcing =
Paid Data, we=E2=80=99re also introducing the US dollar as i) the primary m=
eans to purchase data and / or plans from Pollen, and ii) the means in whic=
h Flower owners will be paid for hauling data.=E2=80=9D And then <a href=3D=
"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30369314.268448/aHR0cHM6Ly9t=
ZWRpdW0uY29tL0Bwb2xsZW5tb2JpbGUvY3JlYXRpbmctYS1yZWFsLW5ldHdvcmstM2Y4NGQ0ZTE=
wZGQx/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd671628d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> another one saying</a>:=
</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Pollen=E2=80=99s mission has always been focus=
ed on building a real network delivering real utility. Over the past year, =
we=E2=80=99ve been focused on achieving that goal, delivering a number of i=
ndustry firsts.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In doing so, we=E2=80=99ve also learned a lot =
of industry firsts, including two critical, hard truths.</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A wireless network that doesn=E2=80=
=99t have a clear path to profitability via paid data is not a viable netwo=
rk</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A token-only model is not a pat=
h to a commercially viable mobile network, particularly in the current regu=
latory environment</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After coming to these conclusions, we determin=
ed the best path forward towards building a viable network =E2=80=94 includ=
ing the introduction of US dollar data payments =E2=80=94 and communicated =
that to the community as soon as possible.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Those two =E2=80=9Chard truths=E2=80=9D strike=
 me as completely, obviously correct,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#f=
ootnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: non=
e !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-blo=
ck;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0but people are understandably mad about this. Lovely <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30369314.268448/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb2=
5ub3JidWlsZHNpbnB1YmxpYy5zdWJzdGFjay5jb20vcC9kZXdpcy1maXJzdC1ydWctcHVsbD9zZ=
D1wZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC3a9e7a71" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> writes</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Upon first glance, the post was bullish. =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0Even the introduction of the good old U.S. dollar as a means to=
 pay for data transfer seemed bullish and sensible. After all, which boomer=
 TradWi (traditional wireless) corporation do you know of that is willing t=
o buy, hold, and sell an illiquid crypto token that trades on one janky DEX=
 to pay for data transfer on a fledgling CBRS network?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Things took a definitive turn for the worse as=
 readers realized that there would be no buy (let alone buy and burn) mecha=
nism to accrue the value of this dollar-denominated data demand to the netw=
ork=E2=80=99s native token that all the earliest builders of the network ha=
d been compensated in! The entire ethos of a decentralized, crypto-powered,=
 community-built wireless network had been thrown out the window.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fast-forwarding to the present, it=E2=80=99s s=
afe to say that the community is outraged, accusations of a rug pull abound=
, and many in DeWi are very disillusioned and disappointed by this decision=
.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well, yes! One vision of DeWi, sorry, is that=
=C2=A0<em>everything will be crypto: </em>The service will be so useful and=
 essential that everyone will have no choice but to use its tokens, and cry=
pto exchanges will respond to the demand by becoming easier for regular peo=
ple to use, and regulators will respond to the public clamor for DeWi token=
s by saying =E2=80=9Csure whatever sell those tokens, they=E2=80=99re not s=
ecurities, you don=E2=80=99t need to register them.=E2=80=9D And in Februar=
y 2022 that was not=C2=A0<em>such=C2=A0</em>a crazy thing to think, and bui=
lding this in crypto provided the =E2=80=9Ctokenomics=E2=80=9D that made pe=
ople want to set up these wireless devices and join the network and do the =
whole thing.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But in January 2023 it is clear that=C2=A0<em>=
the crypto part is a drawback:=C2=A0</em>If you build an excellent widespre=
ad wireless network and go out to consumers and corporate customers and say=
 =E2=80=9Chey we have a great network, you should use it, just buy our cryp=
to token,=E2=80=9D they will say =E2=80=9Chmm sounds good except for the to=
ken.=E2=80=9D So you get rid of the token, and all the tokenomics fall apar=
t, and the people who bought in because they thought they=E2=80=99d get ric=
h off the token feel cheated.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also another, related point is that as far as =
I can tell every decentralized crypto project has some central group of dec=
ision-makers who actually run the project,=C2=A0and then a veneer of decent=
ralization. Shouldn=E2=80=99t the holders of Pollen tokens get to decide on=
 its monetization strategy? Lol, no, absolutely not. Sure if they were=C2=
=A0<em>shareholders=C2=A0</em>of Pollen they=E2=80=99d have some legally bi=
nding governance rights. But they=E2=80=99re not.</p>
