<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A reader=C2=A0emailed yesterday to ask:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If Congress ever bans stock buybac=
ks, could a responsible CFO do some token security fraud and settle at an u=
nreasonably large value to return money to shareholders in a tax efficient =
way?</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am not going to explain this!=C2=A0It seems =
a little extreme, but also I love it? I=E2=80=99m not sure that it=E2=80=99=
s actually more tax-efficient than paying a dividend,<a class=3D"footnote-i=
ndex" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; dis=
play: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> and in any case surely paying a dividend is=C2=A0<em>overall=C2=A0</em=
>more efficient than this plan, because the securities-fraud angle involves=
 paying a large cut to lawyers and also to former shareholders. But if Cong=
ress ever bans stock buybacks,=C2=A0some investment bank had better model u=
p this idea.</p>
